1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,860
As you've started to see, working with the right variables is so important.

2

00:00:04,860  -->  00:00:07,740
If an application asks you for your age

3

00:00:07,740  -->  00:00:11,340
to surprise you on your birthday with an age-appropriate gift,

4

00:00:11,340  -->  00:00:15,720
you'll need to make sure that the users can only upload an integer.

5

00:00:15,720  -->  00:00:18,840
If they upload a string or a float decimal,

6

00:00:18,840  -->  00:00:23,180
then it could throw off your app for your user and make it not work.

7

00:00:23,180  -->  00:00:25,580
Thanks to int and float functions,

8

00:00:25,580  -->  00:00:31,600
we can use these to convert strings to integers and floating point numbers respectively.

9

00:00:31,600  -->  00:00:33,615
Let's see some examples.

10

00:00:33,615  -->  00:00:37,890
In this example, the user will be prompted to input their age,

11

00:00:37,890  -->  00:00:42,590
and this will only accept a number integer as an input.

12

00:00:42,590  -->  00:00:47,290
In this example, the user will be prompted to input their height,

13

00:00:47,290  -->  00:00:51,470
and this will only accept a float decimal as an input.

14

00:00:51,470  -->  00:00:54,170
Then if you had those variables,

15

00:00:54,170  -->  00:00:56,850
you can put them into a string and know that

16

00:00:56,850  -->  00:01:00,270
the data types will make sense for your inputs.

17

00:01:00,270  -->  00:01:06,110
As we see here, the int function converts the input string to an integer,

18

00:01:06,110  -->  00:01:10,930
and the float function converts the input string to a floating-point number.

19

00:01:10,930  -->  00:01:14,590
Let's look at the n function with an example.

20

00:01:14,590  -->  00:01:18,510
Now, when we write age equals,

21

00:01:18,510  -->  00:01:27,135
and then we have an input of enter your age with a space and an end parentheses,

22

00:01:27,135  -->  00:01:29,070
and then another end parenthesis.

23

00:01:29,070  -->  00:01:31,780
Now, when we execute this,

24

00:01:31,780  -->  00:01:33,900
we'll be able to put in an age.

25

00:01:33,900  -->  00:01:39,620
Now, notice how we can add in the input as a number at 21,

26

00:01:39,620  -->  00:01:44,180
and then this works as expected and your age is 21.

27

00:01:44,180  -->  00:01:49,340
But what happens if we don't write the number like that?

28

00:01:49,340  -->  00:01:51,840
So if we execute this code,

29

00:01:51,840  -->  00:01:56,200
and we were to put to space one as we'll

30

00:01:56,200  -->  00:02:00,460
try adding a space between these two numbers and then press enter.

31

00:02:00,460  -->  00:02:02,665
This leads to a value error.

32

00:02:02,665  -->  00:02:07,655
If we were to write this again and execute the code.

33

00:02:07,655  -->  00:02:11,430
If we were to enter a string into our input field,

34

00:02:11,430  -->  00:02:15,130
such as hello world, and press enter.

35

00:02:15,130  -->  00:02:17,830
We get another value error as it's

36

00:02:17,830  -->  00:02:21,050
expecting a number input and not a string, but we put in a string.

37

00:02:21,050  -->  00:02:24,070
This can be quite helpful, such as, for example,

38

00:02:24,070  -->  00:02:27,210
telling the user in an application that they need to enter in a number

39

00:02:27,210  -->  00:02:30,830
to proceed if they're putting in the wrong type of input.

40

00:02:30,830  -->  00:02:34,715
Now let's look at the float function with an example.

41

00:02:34,715  -->  00:02:39,840
Write height equals float input,

42

00:02:39,840  -->  00:02:43,260
enter your height at a space,

43

00:02:43,260  -->  00:02:48,225
and then end quotes parenthesis and then another end parentheses.

44

00:02:48,225  -->  00:02:50,660
Now, when we execute this code,

45

00:02:50,660  -->  00:02:55,415
notice how we can add in an input such as an integer, gamble 100.

46

00:02:55,415  -->  00:02:57,740
Then this will work as expected.

47

00:02:57,740  -->  00:03:02,540
If we press enter, this adds in the number and it prints out the string.

48

00:03:02,540  -->  00:03:06,140
If we were to copy this code and run this again,

49

00:03:06,140  -->  00:03:11,575
and we do 1.5 as a floating point number, and press enter.

50

00:03:11,575  -->  00:03:14,170
This also works as expected.

51

00:03:14,170  -->  00:03:18,190
But let's see an example where if we

52

00:03:18,190  -->  00:03:23,125
put in foot and inches as quotation marks, for example.

53

00:03:23,125  -->  00:03:29,970
Let's say we write one single five double quote for feet and inches,

54

00:03:29,970  -->  00:03:32,830
and we were to press enter to enter in our height.

55

00:03:32,830  -->  00:03:36,250
We're going to get a value error since Python is not

56

00:03:36,250  -->  00:03:39,890
able to convert this string into a float.

57

00:03:39,890  -->  00:03:44,790
To make this work, we need to either use a library to convert the string equivalent

58

00:03:44,790  -->  00:03:48,230
of this to an integer or

59

00:03:48,230  -->  00:03:52,410
floating point number to use before sending this two-input function.

60

00:03:52,410  -->  00:03:55,330
As you see in these other two examples,

61

00:03:55,330  -->  00:03:59,670
the int function converts the input string to an integer,

62

00:03:59,670  -->  00:04:03,470
and the float function converts the input string to a floating point number.

63

00:04:03,470  -->  00:04:08,050
Here and here. Now, let's combine inputs and outputs.

64

00:04:08,050  -->  00:04:11,910
Let's say you want to convert the outputs together that you

65

00:04:11,910  -->  00:04:16,360
have in other cells into a single string. How would we do that?

66

00:04:16,360  -->  00:04:19,240
Remember our previous lesson on F strings.

67

00:04:19,240  -->  00:04:23,890
We already have our age and height variables defined previously.

68

00:04:23,890  -->  00:04:25,680
Let's execute those again.

69

